36 hours since we saw this video for the first time, it is still maddening to see. FYI JCPenney issued this on December 21:

"We are deeply disturbed by the incident that took place at our Jefferson Mall store, in which one customer made extremely inappropriate remarks to two other customers while standing in the checkout line. We regret that innocent bystanders –both other customers and a JCPenney associate– were subjected to such discriminatory remarks. We absolutely do not tolerate this behavior in our stores, and are working with our associates to ensure any future incidents of this nature will be addressed quickly and appropriately. In the meantime, JCPenney is asking for the community's help in identifying the two women who were targeted for such remarks, as we would like to reimburse them for their entire purchase and offer a sincere apology for their experience."

More here: http://www.latinorebels.com/2016/12/21/racist-anti-latino-viral-video-from-kentucky-go-back-wherever-the-fck-you-come-from-lady/

status_message:
Via National Day Laborer Organizing Network

Los Angeles— On Saturday, Los Jornaleros del Norte will release their fourth album "Chant Down the Walls," which covers issues relevant to the day laborer community across the country. Los Jornaleros, are well known as the "house band" for the Immigrant Rights movement in Los Angeles and have played at nearly every mass mobilization or protest in support of immigrant rights for over a decade.

Their music not only reflects the political issues of day laborers but have an important tool in generating consciousness throughout local communities and day laborer street corners. They use their music as a way to tell the stories of day laborers and as a way to educate each other on some of the issue the community face.

status_message:
Rebeldes in El Bronx: This October 26, it's time to enjoy a historic digital media event.

audioBoom and The New York Public Library Present: 

 Live from El Bronx: A Latino Rebels Radio Special Event 

For the first time, #LatinoRebelsRadio will record their weekly podcast in front of a live audience.

The live October 26 event will include a discussion about the Puerto Rican community in the Bronx and in NYC. What does the future hold for our community in the borough? This conversation will explore our history, the context(s) of the newly coined label of "piano district," other topics around neighborhood gentrification and the arts.

You have the chance to be there! Visit this Eventbrite page and reserve your seat: https://www.eventbrite.com/e/live-from-el-bronx-a-latino-rebels-radio-special-event-tickets-28419170504?aff=emailinvitation 

Hosted by: Julio Ricardo Varela, Host of Latino Rebels Radio

Our panel of experts includes:

Melissa  Mark Viverito, Speaker of the New York City Council @MMViverito

Charlie Vázquez, Author, Consultant and Director of the Bronx Writers Center @charlievazquez

Liza Colón-Zayas, Award-winning Actress and playwright (Between the Riverside and Crazy, Dexter) @nycbatwife 

Bill Aguado, Interim Executive Director at En Foco @billaguado

Ramon Da Silva, Reference Librarian

JOIN US: Come over to the Bronx Library Center and participate in this lively conversation. Space is limited so all attendees must RSVP.

Doors open at 6:00pm.
Latino Rebels Radio is a live podcast every Sunday at 10:00 pm EST discussing current news, engaging in political humor, facilitating social commentary and providing an analysis of the US Latino world. Hosted by Julio Ricardo Varela and Sharis Delgadillo. Produced by Christian Henriquez. Distributed by audioBoom. www.latinorebels.com Twitter: @latinorebels

Media Sponsor:
audioBoom is the leading spoken-word audio platform for hosting, distributing and monetizing content. The platform receives over 35 million listens per month and allows audio producers to share their content via iTunes, Google Play, Stitcher, Facebook, Twitter, as well as their own websites and mobile apps. Twitter: @audioBoom.

status_message:
The Statewide Hispanic Chamber of Commerce of New Jersey Presents: Latino Rebels Town Hall Mixer- Latino Vote 2016: Economy

For our second edition of the Latino Rebels Town Hall Mixers, we discuss the economic issues affecting the Latino community. Where are the jobs? How can Latinos be self-sustained and self-create work? What is "community equity building" from a financial standpoint? How can we support Latino-owned small businesses and foster growth? More importantly, what are the economic issues we need to measure during this election cycle
This nonpartisan discussion is an opportunity to engage with experts, voice your opinions and share your main concerns.

MODERATOR: Julio Ricardo Varela, Futuro Media Group (NPR's Latino USA) and Founder of Latino Rebels

Panelists:

Hon. Wilda Díaz, Mayor of the City of Perth Amboy: She's the first female to hold that office and currently the only elected Latina mayor in the State of New Jersey.

Lili Gil Valletta: Award-winning entrepreneur, World Economic Forum YGL, TV contributor and President of XL Alliance.

Carlos Medina, Esq.: President of Robinson Aerial a small mapping and engineering company and Chairman of the Statewide Hispanic Chamber of Commerce of New Jersey.

When: Wednesday, April 27, 2016- 6:00 PM EST

Where: SAINT PETER'S UNIVERSITY
            The Jesuit University of New Jersey
            2641 Kennedy Boulevard
            Jersey City, New Jersey 07306


RSVP: This event is free and open to the public.
link_name: Latino Rebels Town Hall Mixer- Latino Vote 2016: Economy

status_message: Our site is currently down. We are in the middle of fixing the issue. Smoke em if you got em.

Residente speaking at March 31 Bernie Sanders rally. NOTE: the live feed was lost for about 1 min. (you can see full speech here: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=n9SKwFOaRFA&ab_channel=ElectionNews)

THIS IS THE TEXT THAT GOT LOST WHEN THE FEED WE WERE WATCHING WENT DOWN:

"And this is the best one: People in Puerto Rico cannot vote for the President of the United States. In other words, we are not allowed to choose the person who makes crucial decisions regarding our country. I didn't come here to complain, but rather put things in proper context. 

You may wonder, what I'm doing here? A person like me with all this information has come to the Bronx to support a candidate for the U.S. presidency. I will explain. I support Bernie Sanders because he has been the only candidate with logical proposals and has expressed support with my country's debt relief. He did not come up to support us now, in the middle of an election cycle to win votes, but he spoke out from the moment the economic crisis began. I support Bernie Sanders because I think he is the most honest candidate there is. I support Bernie Sanders because he is the only candidate who furiously stands up and defends human rights and the rights of the LGBT community.

status_message:
In Austin, Texas - Obama's arrival at #SXSW was not met without protest. 

Pro-immigrant rights group University Leadership Initiative, a local affiliate of United We Dream, demanded President Obama to repeal the 287 (G) federal program allowing local police enforcement officers power to identify, detain, and deport undocumented people. 

The group rallied where Obama was scheduled to appear at a fundraiser for the Democratic National Convention, after his keynote at the SXSW Interactive kickoff on Friday, March 11.

"It's not just about technology. Texas also has the largest construction business in the country," said Alonzo Mendoza member of University Leadership Initiative also seen in this picture. "Many of these construction workers are undocumented. So this is also about recognizing their value." 

Under the Obama administration there has been more deportation than under any other presidency. Texas is the second largest population of undocumented immigrants in the country. (Photo courtesy of University Leadership Initiative) #SXSW2016

status_message:
Community Calls on ICE to Stop the Deportations of Oscar, Wildin and Bilmer #Durham #NC

Durham, NC -  Family, friends and community members are hosting a public vigil tonight to call on Immigration and Customs Enforcement to stop the deportations of three asylum-seeking Central American teenagers. Oscar Alfredo Hernandez Sanchez (A# 206-736-251) of Charlotte, Wildin David Guillen Acosta (A# 206-799-049) of Durham and Bilmer Araeli Pujoy Juarez (A# 202-129-863) of Greenville were the victims of ICE raids earlier this week. All three came to the United States fleeing gang violence.

The vigil will begin at 7pm at the Iglesia Ministerio Nuevo Pentecostal (906 N Hardee St, Durham, NC 27703) on Saturday, January 30, 2016.

status_message:
"The US preference for Cuban migrants is controversial. Under the 1966 Cuban Adjustment Act, once Cubans reach the US border and prove that they're Cuban, they are allowed in with an automatic pathway to permanent residency. None of those benefits are available to Salvadorans or Hondurans who risk thuggish human traffickers, dangerous desert crossings and once they enter the Unites States, the risk of deportation.

"As if on cue, Secretary of State John Kerry announced on Wednesday that the UN High Commissioner for Refugees will now conduct initial screenings in Central America to determine whether people from Honduras, El Salvador and Guatemala qualify for refugee status. Meanwhile, Meissner says US immigraton law's preference for Cubans presents a blatant double standard. 'It is a function of the Cold War. It is based on the assumption that Cubans are persecuted in their country and therefore deserve protection in the United States.'

"Meissner says those things were true at one time, but they definitely have changed since the Obama Administration re-established relations with Havana."

status_message:
The following is video given to Latino Rebels by a student at the University of Puerto Rico. 

The video was taken on May 13 in Old San Juan, when students and teachers were protesting cuts to education given the island's financial crisis. 

The protesters wanted to march to the front of La Fortaleza, where the governor of Puerto Rico lives. In the video, protesters are shouting "We are students, we are not criminals." 

Organizers were asking protesters to peacefully march to the front of La Fortaleza. There was pushing, police appearing to not allow the marchers to pass. At one point a shirt or a blouse is thrown. Organizers ask protesters to act peacefuly but also asked police to let them through. Around 1:30 in, we see a police officer take a club to a protester. It is not clear what happened next.
link_name: May 13: Old San Juan, UPR Student Protests

For Immediate Release: #JessieHernandez Funeral Information

For those who wish to pay their final respects to Jessica Hernandez, the schedule of services is as follows. On Friday, February 6, Jessie's wake will be held from 5 p.m. to 7 p.m. Following the  wake, the Rosary will be prayed from 7 p.m. to 8 p.m. Both the wake and the Rosary will take  place at the Advantage Funeral Home, which is located at 1095 Havana Street, Aurora, Colorado 80010.

Mass will be held on Saturday, February 7, at 10 a.m. at Holy Trinity Church, located at 3050  West 76th Avenue, Westminster, Colorado 80030. The Mass will be immediately followed by  the burial service at Olinger Highland Cemetery, 10201 Grant Street, Thornton, Colorado 80229. 

The Hernandez family has set up an account to accept donations by those who wish to assist with  funeral expenses. The information is as follows: Chase Bank, Account #3044756483. Please note that the bank does not accept cash deposits to this account.
